ont></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dashanvaliant>DashanValiant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/23/03 12:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1588.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  All time favorites</span><hr size=1> <br>
Thief --  No other game gets you into stealth-mode as well as Thief.  And it just oozes atmosphere.  One of the few games that *MUST* be played at expert difficulty to truly experience it.  Utilized both sight and sound fantastically.  I would literally cringe whenever I made noise in that game.  Outfitting yourself for each level based on how well you played the previous was a nice touch as well.  And the ending was true to the spirit of the game.  Ah hell.  I'm gonna have to put this back on the new computer now.<br>
<br>
XCom --  Turn based strategy vs aliens.  Played the demo all to death when it came out.  Then discovered the actual game had world screen aspect as well; where you built bases, and monitored for aliens.  Again, it captured the atmosphere perfectly.  And really, any game where the bad guys can accidentally drop a grenade capable of levelling a city block at their own feet deserves recognition, doesn't it? <br>
<br>
Master of Magic --  Civilization combined with Magic: The Gathering.  Incredible variety of setup ensures that no two games will be even close to the same.  The only real flaw was that the AI was extremely braindead in certain areas.  Touch up the graphics, touch up the AI, make it more stable, rerelease it; instant hit.  <br>
<br>
Half-Life --  The actual single player story was fantastic, but what makes this one of my all time favorites is the fact that they gave out the level building tools.  Mods mods mods.  There is no shortage of additional excellent single player add-ons for HL.  A personal favorite is &quot;They Hunger,&quot; a Night of the Living Dead- type single player game for it.  And also all sorts of multiplayer mods too.  Counter-Strike, Team Fortress, and Day of Defeat to name just the top three.<br>
<br>
There are scads of other games I like and replay, but those are probably the ones I consider the absolute best of the crop.<br>
